Vice President Mike Pence completed his first day in Japan, where he met with Japanese Defense Minister Itsunori Onodera, had a bilateral meeting and joint press conference with Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, and reaffirmed the United States' commitment to the US-Japan alliance. Pence visited the Japanese Ministry of Defense and saw a Patriot missile battery that protects Tokyo, emphasizing the US's dedication to Japan's protection. He also announced that the US will soon unveil the toughest and most aggressive round of economic sanctions on North Korea ever, as part of their maximum pressure campaign. Pence and his wife joined Prime Minister Abe and his wife for a dinner, and tomorrow he will travel to Yokota Air Base to receive a briefing on bilateral ballistic defense capabilities and address members of the Armed Forces. Pence will then travel to Seoul to discuss security and stability on the Korean Peninsula. He will also lead the US delegation to the 2018 Olympic Winter Games in Pyeongchang to reinforce the US presence on the Korean Peninsula and send a message of American resolve to North Korea. This is Pence's second visit to Japan and the Republic of Korea in less than a year.